iStock (iStock) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Niamey - Eight migrants, five of them children, have died of thirst in the Niger desert while making their way to Algeria, a key destination for would-be migrants to Europe, a security source told AFP."These migrants died of thirst on the way to Algeria," the source, who asked not to be identified, said late on Tuesday.The group, a man, a woman and five children aged between six and 12, "were abandoned by a smuggler" and "all died of thirst", he added.Online news site Air-info, which is based in northern Niger, said the eight were part of a larger group headed for Algeria, and that four men who had been rescued were found "completely dehydrated".Last June the bodies of 34 migrants were found in the desert, while in late 2013 a group of 92 Niger citizens, including many women and children, also died of thirst after being abandoned by smugglers.Several thousand Niger citizens living illegally in Algeria have been expelled since 2015 following a deal between the governments of both countries.Niger in 2015 adopted tough legislation against human trafficking that sets jail sentences of up to 30 years for smugglers.24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.